Decided to try this place for the first time after driving by it.  I wasn't impressed by the result of my visit. I asked the gentleman behind the cashier counter if the shawarma is authentic, he said thats how I make my living.  I unexpectedly paid $16 and change for a fairly big sized shawarma, that wasn't authentic, it included a small container of salad, which was useless because there is salad inside the shawarma. A genuine shawarma includes fries inside, when I asked where are the fries, the guy behind the cashier says theres no room because of all the salad toppings, LOL.  I've been to Israel twice, ate plenty of authentic food, this was nowhere close. I've been to many halal and kosher gyro, falafel and shawarma places in NYC, they taste similar to this place, but for half the price.  I couldn't finish the shawarma they served here and ended up throwing it out along with the useless side of salad, its pointless.  Quality of quantity, not the other way around, I wasn't satisfied with spending $16+ on a generous portion of ok food.  Edit: Really disturbing response on yelp by a miserably disgruntled owner. Being rude and insulting a costumer is the lowest thing a business can do. I didn't even dine in, I took it to go. LOL really emotionally sad response by Ms. Leor.

This is a middle eastern/Israeli restaurant which is kosher. This was my first time here and was taking the food to go. They cater mostly to Israeli clients and that's evident by the Hebrew literature and the tv tuned to an Israeli channel. Diners who choose to dine in have the luxury of enjoying their unlimited salad bar but the to go customers get a small plastic container to fill once. The salad bar is filled with great Israeli/ middle eastern classics like fried eggplant, beets, a Eastern European style potato salad and other items which you could easily fill up on. I honestly think this is the draw for a lot of customers. We got the small shawarma plate which comes with rice and a container of the salad bar. It cost $16 plus tax which I think is steep because the portion of meat is not exactly generous but kosher meat does come at a premium cost. The chicken was under seasoned and underwhelming, really nothing special. The rice was just okay but the salad bar items were great and delicious. Another great thing I've noticed is that they make fresh falafel to order and it looked really good so next time I'm definitely going to order it.

Although it offers good tasting food and the establishment itself is very quaint, I personally don't feel like it's a good client value proposition. Places such as Jerusalem Steakhouse Express and similar establishments have the whole salad bar gimmick but offer normal prices as well as high quality main course meals. If prices were averaged out a bit, I see this place becoming more populated and gaining a lot more clients from a broader social class.
